dotcomguy2: just use a nice firewall configuration app or script... dotcomguy2: I have written a list in http://WWW.sabi.co.UK/Notes/linuxFwConfig.html that may be useful dotcomguy2: what worries me is that you have asked a question omitting several vital details. Which tends to imply that you don't consider them vital... dotcomguy2: of all those apps the most comprehensive is probably http://WWW.FwBuilder.org/ dotcomguy2: a lot of people also use Shorewall or similar... dotcomguy2: it all depends on how complicated your situation is. dotcomguy2: the usual situation in this channel is that most people asking questions don't really understand the questions they are asking. It goes downhill from there :-). That's why I usually recommend a GUI frontend. dotcomguy2: you can generate the config on a machine with GUI and load it on another. dotcomguy2: OK, this is a bit better. dotcomguy2: you need to DNAT of course, and ensure that there is some connection tracking or something else to let both incoming and outgoing packets thru. dotcomguy2: but that is a typical case handled by most firewall builders. dotcomguy2: I usually try not to look at people's configs, because it is usually impossible to imagine in one's head how they are going to play out. One needs as a rule 'tcpdump' both before and after the firewall to see what's going on. dotcomguy2: odds are that there are not return packets. dotcomguy2: try to 'tcpdump -nn -i eth0' dotcomguy2: try to 'tcpdump -nn -i eth1' dotcomguy2: you want to see if packets get out of 'eth1' towards 192.168.1.200 and then if packets come back. dotcomguy2: try to 'tcpdump -nn -i eth1 port 10000' dotcomguy2: I am assuming you got a FORWARD rule to let the packets thru... I hope. dotcomguy2: note that INPUT is not FORWARD. dotcomguy2: is 'eth1' on your outside or inside? dotcomguy2: and do you have a suitable FORWARD rule? dotcomguy2: ahhh, then switch to 'eth0'. dotcomguy2: the 'tcpdump'. dotcomguy2: you need also a FORWARD rule to let port 10000 thru, either in general or specifically between 'eth1' and 'eth0'. dotcomguy2: well, so the inner machine is not replying. dotcomguy2: or the replies are being dropped at 'eth0' because there is no rule for port 10000 from 'eth0' to 'eth1'. dotcomguy2: or perhaps you have no 'RELATED,ESTABLISHED' rule in FORWARD. who knows. dotcomguy2: no idea.

perl -e'for$c(qw(utf-8 utf-16be utf-16le utf-32 euc-jp shift-jis)){for$g(" ","|gzip -c"){print "$c$g ".`iconv -c 31757-h.htm -f utf-8 -t $c$g|wc -c`}}' Interestingly the results are far tighter (and better) if you use bzip2 Yes Don't know if it's a correct assumption, though Strangely, xz (LZMA) is slightly worse than bzip2 here You can save ~7% over gzip -9 by using 7z's gzip implementation (...though you wouldn't do that dynamically on a web server because it's way too slow) (but it's good whenever you're precomputing compressed files) a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: The most important thing is the size of the output, since the author's goal is to minimise that and if using a better compression implementation gives you a larger percentage gain than changing the charset, it's probably better for people to focus on the former before worrying too much about the latter I guess so It's more complex to changing the compression code and to make it cached so it goes fast etc so maybe it's better to do dumb stuff like recompress static files on every single request, and make easy changes like reencoding the static file Most compression algorithms seem to be designed to maximise resource usage on compression and minimise on decompression (e.g. LZMA can happily use 1GB RAM to compress, and a tenth of that for decompression) which seems precisely the wrong way around when you're doing compression on a single centralised server, and decompression on a thousand fast unutilised desktop PCs simultaneously

I'm noticing that PICS seems to have been a bit of a failure, don't suppose there's any other machine-readable means of indicating content is PG or not PG ? much point for a microformat, given that I think automated parental guidence software would probably do keyword searches of the content ? will have about 1 million+ examples of hCalendar marked up with cover charges in a day or so. in theory, anyway hrm ? oh, I'm currently working on restoring SL events indexing to my sw.slr project ^basically taking the tag-soup, non-semantic data made available by Linden Lab, and marking it up with microformats http://svc.sl.net.marvulous.co.uk/ hehe toodles

fe5fc1e9bf60926e09f6f91b4e6df403: There's no pricing/cost field in Calendar So you'd have to just include it as part of the event `description` The currency formats stuff is just brainstorming and examples gathering at this point So there's no standard for it The closest we have is <foo class="price">Â¬Â£15</span> which is used in hListing, which is a little more mature. I'm not sure that makes a lot of sense as an abbreviation. Not quite See http://microformats.org/wiki/machine-data the ABBR pattern is suitable for some situations, but the semantics of HTML still apply The content of both the title attribute and the inner text has to be human consumable, and it needs to make semantic sense as an abbreviation at the HTML level Basically, both title and inner text are human-data, but the title may also be a precise format of data so that machines can parse it too. Now, in this case, there's no format for parsing prices There's no microformat. So to have the price included as part of the hCalendar content, you need to ensure that it's within the `description` field of the event. Within that, using class=price makes as much sense as anything (and reuses the classname from hListing) organizer is ideally an hCard for the person/company responsible for the event There's not a lot to it :) Not that I'm aware of, I'm afraid Gotta disappear now. Good luck with your mark-up! Or on the top for that matters. There we go. Ctx.arc(75,75,50,offset,-Math.PI*2*red+offset,true);. Now I just need to understand completely how it solved it XD.

Yes :-) If you set e.g. red=0.99, what the arc() call is doing is taking the point at 'offset' on the second, and then the point that's 0.99 of the way around the circle in a clockwise direction and then you're drawing the arc between those two points in an *anti*-clockwise direction so it only fill 0.01 of the circle What you probably want is for the second point to be 0.99 around anticlockwise instead, so you'd have to use offset-Math.PI*2*red instead of Math.PI*2*red+offset (Uh, "'offset' on the second"? edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: Converting between HTML and XML in the toolchain doesn't seem like a good solution in that situation, since the conversion is lossy (in both directions) - e.g. you can't write a web crawler that parses HTML then stores it in an XML database to do a load of querying on the data, because the translation will destroy some of the data edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: I would imagine any XML toolchain is very likely to serialise to XML at some point, so you've got to restrict yourself to well-formed documents b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: Rather, the conclusion is that there is a benefit if the document format is compatible with the tools you use (without needing ugly munging in the middle), so it'd be good if all were HTML or all were XML or all were anything else edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: That's why I said "e.g. you can't write a web crawler ...", because there are cases where you have no control over the input HTML but you want to make use of useful tools that already exist (and that today are mostly designed for XML) edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: That's why I said "e.g. you can't write a web crawler that parses HTML then stores it in an XML database to do a load of querying on the data" edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: because you've got to use an HTML parser, but then there are other useful tools you'd like to use, and you don't want to have to deal with weird artifacts introduced by the HTML-to-well-formed-XML translation process b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: As I read it, Noah was describing an advantage of XHTML and of its use of layering on XML, which is that such a language would give you that opportunity (in the hypothetical case that people used that language) b25b6b77a0087ff8385941e5545d32ea: and it does indeed seem to be an advantage of XHTML, even if it's overshadowed by the fact that nobody uses XHTML edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: If I write something that e.g. downloads a load of random pages and then tries to count the most common attributes, using some XML database that provides nice easy-to-use efficient querying features, I don't want to be told that there's lots of attributes named "xlinkU0003Ahref" because that's just an artifact of the translation process edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: Also it might irreversibly drop 'xmlns' attributes, so it's impossible to translate the results back accurately The problems aren't insurmountable, they're just a bit of a pain and it'd be nicer if they weren't problems aways edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: I think I forgot whether I was trying to argue for any particular point, but I guess the point was that it seems better to say "HTML not being XML is indeed a problem because it makes it hard to interoperate with XML tools, but it's an unfixable problem so we'll have to reduce its impact and live with it" rather than saying "that's not a problem at all, just stick an HTML parser on your toolchain" but anyway I'm away :-)

Authors will adopt HTML5 over Flash because it makes their lives easier or improves the quality of their product, not because their users explicitly demand it. 70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132, <html lang> is the better bet. I've spent more than two hours reading all my spec mail.  :( But I'm finally done. What? Element attributes are logically unordered.  Use whatever order you like. Are you testing the effect that role is having here in an actual UA that supports role, or just speculatively adding markup in case maybe for someone it would be better than not having the markup? 70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132, don't do the latter, ever.  Do not add features you can't test.  They'll probably make things worse.  UAs can deal with you ignoring their existence, they can't deal with you giving them explicit instructions that turn out to make no sense because you didn't test them. I've learned this the hard way. 70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132, I don't know.  But if you aren't testing, don't use the feature, period.  You *will* do it wrong and your site *will* break when someone finally does implement the feature.  Guaranteed. 70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132, what? 70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132, I've seen The Matrix.  I have no idea what you mean in context. No, that is an absolutely terrible idea.  Drop it immediately.  You're doing a disservice to yourself and your users and the web as a whole.  Deploying a feature that hasn't yet been implemented is almost guaranteed to break, and that either 1) hurts your users if their site breaks, or (worse) 2) hurts browsers because they get complaints from users that the site breaks in the new version, since the new version implements the feature you're u sing brokenly. What will happen is that either you will misunderstand the spec somehow, or else the implementation will have some quirk you weren't expecting.  I have had this happen to me *multiple* times. When I learned that Opera supposed datalist, I added support to MediaWiki and tested in Opera -- only to find out that actually there was a slight quirk I never would have predicted that made it behave worse than the non-datalist functionality. When I learned that Opera supported attributes like pattern on inputs, I added pattern to lots of inputs, and tested.  It turned out that if a password field fails a constraint, it will print the value of the password field in plaintext. In both cases, if I had blindly added the feature without testing it in any actual user-agent, it would have caused significant *harm* to users when Opera added the feature. In another case, when I was young and stupid and didn't yet realize the absolute necessity of testing, I added a handheld stylesheet to MediaWiki without having any mobile UA handy, figuring something was better than nothing.  This actually broke Opera Mobile (or Mini or something), to the point that they went to the effort to dig up wikitech-l and ask there for us to remove our handheld stylesheet because it was broken. If you care about blind users, then yes, absolutely test in JAWS. Add whatever features demonstrably make your users' experience better. Do not add features that don't do anything and might or might not do something in the future just because you can. Semantics for semantics' sake is just as bad. Keep this in mind: if you use role nowhere at all, your page will be like 99.9% of pages out there.  Screen readers for the blind will be able to handle that. So it will work fine. If you use role *incorrectly*, your site will work *worse*.  It might become unusable, even. The gains are not worth the risk from any kind of practical standpoint. 70bfd0ae2cfbf2da192bddd569cf6132, that's a string of buzzwords, not an actual reason. An example of a reason to use role="something or other" would be "so JAWS does X instead of Y". Where X is better than Y. that would suck give me browsers with different capabilities and different bugs, so each browser can see what it's doing wrong D: at one point i tried implementing image zooming, eg. like mousewheel zooming in an image viewer; you see some interesting behavior between browsers there, the different optimization strategies become very visible eg. FF (3.6 at the time, IIRC) seemed to scale images at paint time, so rendering is a little slow, but if you zoom in on a big image it's fairly consistent whereas chrome (8? 9?), IIRC, seemed to scale the entire image just once when you changed the scale; rendering was much faster, but there was a huge hitch whenever the zoom level changed this was just CSS scaling and differences in the browser's internal image scaling methods well, for the particular case that's all I wanted (it was an image viewer, so nearest scaling would have been too low-quality) but yeah I wish it was possible to more directly hint the scaling algorithm, between nearest (very fast), bilinear (fast/decent quality), and slower, high-quality scaling the sort of UI I was looking for was eg. mousewheel zooming in and out in Photoshop ... i should probably revisit it since both chrome and FF have had a major release since then this is just zooming the image with CSS eg. with a large (say, 3000x3000) image, zooming in a notch would freeze for 500ms or so in chrome presumably (guessing based on behavior, didn't look at the code) resizing the entire image, even though only a small portion was visible which makes a lot of sense for certain use cases--just not mine nah modern browsers can handle images that size easily normally it just shows a downscaled version ff4 is much better than 3.6 was at painting large, scaled images, it seems 3.6 had a fast path for that (scrolling only horizontally or vertically, obviously optimized for scrollbars), but if you did both at once it would get ugly looks like ff4 optimized that in the general case if you're in a RAM-constrained environment you're not viewing print-resolution images :) (that's why the low-res versions exist; . . . that just leaves the fact that named entities are syntax errors. Okay, so apparently if you use <!DOCTYPE html>, named entities become XML well-formedness errors, so it's impossible to use XMLHttpRequest. This seems like a pretty significant problem.  Is there any way around it?  If not, can some other kind of doctype be allowed that doesn't trigger it? looks at Hixie Okay, let's assume that I'm not willing to find every single use of named entities in an application that's several hundred thousand LOC with gigabytes of content in the database. So you're saying don't use XHR, make people use <iframe>s instead? Surely that must have some disadvantages?  To begin with, it breaks all legacy codebases that expect XHR to work, so it's sort of out of the question for me right now. I thought <!doctype html> was chosen so that it had no significant compat issues. It seems like there's no way to have a valid HTML5 document that contains a named entity and works with XHR? a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2, doesn't seem like it: http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/multipage/syntax.html#the-doctype So in other words do XHR, but instead of using requestXML, create an iframe and stick requestText into its innerHTML or such. is wondering if html5 mandates Accept headers depending on the tag (html) or property (css) used. for now, it's kind of nightmarish and create issues for Web development. a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: once/when the html file is downloaded by the browser, other resources are being requested by an HTTP GET Let's say in the case of IMG <img src="http://example.net/toto"/> Firefox sends Accept: image/png,image/*;q=0.8,*/*;q=0.5 which is cool but webkit seems to send "*/*" and Opera and Opera text/html, application/xml;q=0.9, application/xhtml+xml, application/x-obml2d, image/png, image/jpeg, image/gif, image/x-xbitmap, */*;q=0.1 the issue popped up last week end in a real case and killed one of our site The <img src="http://example.net/toto"/> was on a very high trafic Web site. unfortunately the URI was an html resource and not an image. ooops s/and not an image/but an image/ rha tired unfortunately the URI was an html resource and not an image. so the little site sent thousands of html file by minutes and eventually died One of the way to avoid it would have been when you see this "Accept: image/*" and the URI is known to be html, reply with a "406 Not Acceptable" 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: the big site with high trafic was not under the control of the little guy. Basically it creates a (not voluntary) DDOS :) Accept could have been a way but not in the state of implementations so far in Rails it took only 2 minutes to implement the method to filter on the Accept and URI combinations, but was working  only with firefox

Ideally you only have one config file. Normally I do. MaartenB: I have a file called server_config.php which is include()'d - it just define()s stuff like database, emails, options etc. This is different in dev / staging / production and is never moved between them. For example, in dev and staging, I have a define which causes a yellow label to appear on the site saying "dev" or "staging" Also in dev, all emails go to me rather than their intended recipient Staging is really to demo stuff to the client before it goes live, and test major new releases on the production server without putting it on the production site I don't put every new revision up on staging, some go straight from dev -> live likewise, I don't always put every new revision up on live, some only ever go as far as staging MaartenB: Of course one should never have production data in a dev / staging database; however, to avoid confusion I also usually have all mails go to me. theDan: There are a lot of issues with such a game, but it can probably be done DShadow: No, I mean that the dev site shouldn't have (sensitive) production data in its database - even though it has a different database Hence real users will never receive emails from the dev site, even if I switch the emails to live mode That is tricky. Carefully. I might occasionally make a "sanitised" version of the production data with all personal data removed theDan: No, I don't think so theDan: It *CAN* be done and the ajax bit is not really the tricky bit. The gameplay is however. Ok, if you have no sensitive data in the db, don't worry about it. Or if all the data belongs to you personally, fine. But if it's other peoples' data, that is tricky. Drakas: I disagree, doing it in browser+php is probably not too bad, but there are many issues. It would certainly be easier for users as they don't have aything to install I'm sure that a tick-based RPG is quite feasible Well, only if you send all the data for a move in one go. Also, how often are they going to happen? Not too frequently I imagine. Obviously not having server-push in AJAX is tricky. I did try to implement it (and succeeded) but the PHP was pretty nasty and I have a feeling it wouldn't scale very well. Using the "continuously loading http request" method, which is nasty Even in Mozilla with its true server-push XMLHttpRequest it's still nasty on the server-side Drakas: It should work either way, but the overhead of loading php-cgi is higher. I used a complicated system of server-side unix sockets blocking to synchronise requests, it was icky. It would still work in cgi though. whatever solution you use, you likely be in the milliseconds range for accuracy. the select() call on linux allows for nanoseconds, but this is more a theoretical value. yes, you can pass nanoseconds to select() You can of course communicate rather easily over any device.
